1. Introduction¶

The advent of big data has revolutionised many industries as it enables them to obtain insights from their analyses which they weren't necessarily able to achieve with traditional data [1]. In the field of law enforcement there are multiple use cases, which includes the analysis and prediction of crime [2]. This report will therefore harness the insights that can be obtained from big data to analyse the claims made in the television documentary Ross Kemp and the Armed Police broadcast on 6th September 2018.

Big data can be defined by the size of the dataset, which may reach "tens or hundreds of gigabytes to petabytes" [3]. Other definitions avoid quantification and instead define big data by its processing and analytical requirements, which cannot be met by traditional IT infrastructure [4]. The street level crime data file used in this assessment is approximately 13GB in size when uncompressed and cannot be processed locally on the author's laptop, therefore cloud computing resources will be utilised.

Although the aforementioned dataset provides observations up to May 2021, the main aim of this project is to assess the validity of the three claims at the time they were broadcast in September 2018. This will be done using a combination of exploratory data analysis, traditional statistical techniques such as correlation, and time series forecasting. The objective of the latter is to determine what forecasts could have been made at the time of the broadcast with the data available, then compare the predictions with the actual data.

The claims made relate to the UK as a whole, however the street level crime data file contains details of offences committed in England, Wales and Northern Ireland, but not Scotland. Likewise, the 'LSOA_pop_v2' csv file containing the populations for each Lower Layer Super Output Area (LSOA) apply to England and Wales, not Northern Ireland. Consequently, this study will only use data from England and Wales to ensure consistency.

There is also a problem with the street level crime data file. Firearms offences cannot be distinguished from the given crime types in the dataset, which is problematic given that these offences need to be analysed in claims 2 and 3. It was suggested that 'possession of weapons' offences resulting in a prison sentence be used to form the basis of the analysis, as firearms possession carries a mandatory term of imprisonment. This approach is not considered feasible as it excludes various other types of firearm offence in England and Wales that do not result in a mandatory prison sentence [5].

Instead, the police recorded crime and outcomes open data tables published by the Home Office were used as they include all three classifications of firearms offence [6]. The data tables below were downloaded then combined to create a csv file called 'firearms_data' after all other offence types were filtered out.

  • Police recorded crime open data Community Safety Partnership tables from year ending March 2008 to year ending March 2011.
  • Police recorded crime Community Safety Partnership open data tables, from year ending March 2012 to year ending March 2015.
  • Police recorded crime Community Safety Partnership open data tables, from year ending March 2016 to year ending March 2023.

The data provides the number of offences in each Community Safety Partnership (CSP) area, rather than by LSOA. Therefore, data from the UK's Office for National Statistics (ONS) Open Geography Portal [7] was used to create an 'area_lookups' csv file that translates LSOA codes to CSP codes. This will be used to map the drugs offences in the street level crime data file to their relevant CSP area using their LSOA code, so they can then be combined with the firearms data for the analysis of claim 3. The module tutor has been granted access to both the 'firearms_data' and 'area_lookups' csv files, which are stored in a folder in the author's University OneDrive account.

Big data analysis will be undertaken on a Linux Virtual Machine (VM) procured through Microsoft Azure in a Docker container running PySpark. The datasets are saved in Azure blob storage and will be accessed from this Jupyter Notebook.

Initially, the 'Sample_1pc_Data' csv file containing a small subset of the street level crime data file will be used to speed up development. This will be processed on a VM with 2 vCPUs, 8GB RAM and a standard SSD. When the full street level crime data file is ready to be processed, the VM will be upgraded to 4 vCPUs, 16GB RAM and a premium 256GB SSD. This is being done to accelerate the intensive shuffle operations that will be executed in PySpark. In addition to upgrading the VM, the SparkSession parameters will be reconfigured to improve I/O efficiency during these operations [8]. Moreover, those shuffle operations used solely for development purposes will be 'commented out' when the full street level crime data file is processed.

4. Using Statistics, Visualisation Methods and Machine Learning to Interrogate Claim 1¶

Initially, it is useful to employ visualisations in an exploratory manner to gain an understanding of how the data is structured and whether any patterns may be present [9]. Trends feature regularly in crime data [10] and research has shown that many crimes exhibit seasonality [11], therefore it is anticipated that both will be present in this dataset.

To test this assumption, a line chart is utilised first to check whether trend or seasonality may be present. If so, it is important to decompose time series data like this to confirm whether these components exist, which in turn will help inform subsequent decisions about which analytical techniques to use next [12]. Consistency is often a feature of crime seasonality and research shows that violent crimes in particular are more likely to occur in the summer [13]. Consequently, additive decomposition is preferred in this case as it is "more appropriate when the seasonal factors tend to be steady from one year to the next" [9].

The dataset provides observations each month from December 2010 to May 2021, however the claim was made in a broadcast on 6th September 2018. This provides an opportunity to forecast the time series using the data that was available at this point in time, whilst looking 'into the future' to see what observations were recorded after the broadcast. This is a useful endeavour because it highlights whether it was reasonable to make the claim at the time, based on the available data. Moreover, it enables an analysis of the models used to forecast the time series.

Seasonal AutoRegressive Integrated Moving Average (SARIMA) models have been shown to be effective at forecasting crime trends [14] and one study has shown that "higher fitting and forecasting accuracy" can be achieved using ARIMA compared to exponential smoothing [15, p.627]. Conversely, others have shown that the latter provides a high level of accuracy when short-term forecasting using city-level data is undertaken to predict crime in smaller geographical areas [16]. SARIMA and Holt-Winters Exponential Smoothing (HWES) can each handle time series data where trend and seasonality are present, therefore both will be employed in this study given their apparent utility in forecasting crime.

The presence of trend and seasonality means the time series is unlikely to be stationary and this will be checked using the Augmented Dickey Fuller (ADF) test. If this assumption is correct, the trend will need to be eliminated to achieve stationarity before the SARIMA model is implemented. This step is not required when using an exponential smoothing model as they are all inherently non-stationary [17].

Grid search will be used to find the optimum parameters for the SARIMA model, including d which dictates how many times differencing should be applied to make the time series stationary. Differencing is unlikely to achieve stationarity if more than 3 rounds are required [18], therefore the diff() function in Pandas will be used first to ascertain the possible value of d. If stationarity cannot be achieved in 3 or less applications of the function, the time series will be made stationary using another method before the grid search is implemented. Otherwise, the stationarity problem will be left to the SARIMA model to handle using the optimum value of d found during the search when the lowest Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) value is identified. The remaining parameters will be kept as low as possible as higher values can lead to overfitting [18].

The models will be trained on monthly data collected over a period of 6 years and 9 months, from December 2010 to August 2017. As such, it is highly unlikely they will be able to predict long-term cyclical fluctuations which may be present in data collected over a longer period. Therefore, the models will be tested on a 12-month set covering the period September 2017 to August 2018. This is deemed sufficient for the purpose of this study, which is to consider whether violent crimes were increasing at the point the claim was made on 6th September 2018.

Once the models have been trained, their Mean Absolute Error (MAE), Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) and Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) will be calculated. The best performing model will then be identified by comparing these metrics against one another.

# Create function for ADF test then check dataset for stationarity
def ADF_test(timeseries, dataDesc):
    print('Reason for Test =', dataDesc)
    dftest = adfuller(timeseries.dropna(), autolag='AIC')
    print('Test statistic = {:.3f}'.format(dftest[0]))
    print('P-value = {:.3f}'.format(dftest[1]))
    print('Critical values :')
    for k, v in dftest[4].items():
        print('\t{}: {} - The data is {} stationary with {}% confidence' \
              .format(k, v, 'not' if v<dftest[0] else '', 100-int(k[:-1])))

# Use grid search to find optimal parameters for SARIMA model 
p = d = q = range(0, 2)
seasonal_period = 12
pdq = list(itertools.product(p, d, q))
seasonal_pdq = [(x[0], x[1], x[2],seasonal_period) for x in list(itertools.product(p, d, q))]

for param in pdq:
    for param_seasonal in seasonal_pdq:
        try:
            mod =\
            sm.tsa.statespace.SARIMAX(train,
                                      order=param,
                                      seasonal_order=param_seasonal,
                                      enforce_invertibility=False,
                                     enforce_stationarity=False)
            results = mod.fit()
            print('ARIMA{}x{} - AIC:{}'.format(param, param_seasonal, results.aic))
        except Exception as ex:
            print(ex)
            continue

Compare SARIMA & HWES Models¶

In [26]:
### SARIMA Model MAE, RMSE & MAPE Calculations

# Predicted values and actual values
sar_predicted_values = sar_forecast_values.values
sar_actual_values = test.values.flatten()

# Mean Absolute Error (MAE)
sar_mae = np.mean(np.abs(sar_predicted_values - sar_actual_values))

# Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE)
sar_mse = np.mean((sar_predicted_values - sar_actual_values) ** 2)
sar_rmse = np.sqrt(sar_mse)

# Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE)
sar_mape = np.mean(np.abs((sar_predicted_values - sar_actual_values) / sar_actual_values)) * 100


### HWES Model MAE, RMSE & MAPE Calculations

# Predicted values and actual values
hwes_predicted_values = hwes_forecast.values
hwes_actual_values = test.values.flatten()

# Mean Absolute Error (MAE)
hwes_mae = np.mean(np.abs(hwes_predicted_values - hwes_actual_values))

# Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE)
hwes_mse = np.mean((hwes_predicted_values - hwes_actual_values) ** 2)
hwes_rmse = np.sqrt(hwes_mse)

# Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE)
hwes_mape = np.mean(np.abs((hwes_predicted_values - hwes_actual_values) / hwes_actual_values)) * 100


### Summarise the figures in a dataframe to ease comparison 
x = [['SARIMA', sar_mae, sar_rmse, sar_mape], ['HWES', hwes_mae, hwes_rmse, hwes_mape]]
df = pd.DataFrame(x, columns=['Model', 'MAE', 'RMSE', 'MAPE'])

Figure 1 shows violent crimes rising steadily from the beginning of 2014 to around the time the claim was made. The decomposition plot in figure 2 confirms the presence of the trend, as well as an annual seasonal component. Consequently, the decision to use SARIMA and HWES models to forecast the time series is sound.

It is clear the time series is not stationary, as all three critical values of the ADF test are lower than the test statistic. Two rounds of differencing were able to achieve stationarity, therefore the SARIMA model was left to find the optimum value of d.

The diagnostics plot in figure 3 indicates the SARIMA model fits the data quite well. The distribution in the histogram is not far from being normal, most points in the QQ plot cluster on or around the straight line, and all of the lags in the correlogram are contained within the confidence band. Furthermore, the standardized residual appears to be close to the ideal value of zero [11].

Figures 4 and 5 show both 12- and 24-month forecasts for the SARIMA and HWES models, including the 95% confidence intervals for the shorter forecast. The 12-month forecasts are relatively accurate in each case and seem to have encapsulated the trend and seasonality in the data. However, the predicted values appear to digress from the observations toward the end of the 24-month forecast, continuing to follow an upward trend when the actual data starts to plateau. This indicates the models perform better when making short-term predictions and accuracy decreases when forecasts extend beyond 12 months.

Each model performs well over 12 months, but which one is better? It is hard to answer this question solely using visualisations, therefore it is useful to compare some metrics to inform the analysis. Numerous metrics are utilised in the field of time series forecasting because there is no consensus which is best and none captures all the characteristics of a forecast [19]. Here, the MAE, RMSE and MAPE were used to compare the models and the value of each measure for the 12-month forecast is shown in the table above.

The HWES model has lower scores for each measure than SARIMA and therefore performs better in this instance. It's MAE is 4221, which is the average value of the error between the predicted number of violent crimes and the observed number [20]. The RMSE assigns more weight to large errors [21] and in this case is 5248, which indicates there aren't too many sizeable errors as the value is relatively close to the MAE. In isolation, the MAE and RMSE don't quantify the error in relation to the size of the actual values, unlike the MAPE [22]. Again, a lower figure is better and the MAPE of the HWES model is 3.1%, which is very low.

6. Using Statistical Analysis and Evaluation Measures to Interrogate Claims 2 and 3¶

Claim 2 states that there are more firearms incidents per head in Birmingham than anywhere else in the UK. The validity of this statement depends on the time period of the observations being analysed. For example, the claim could be true if the number of firearms incidents over the past 10 years are considered, yet false if this timeframe is restricted to one year. Consequently, it is important to consider how the number of incidents has changed over time. In this case, the data has been aggregated into financial years that cover the period April 2012 to March 2018. This will enable CSP areas to be compared against one another each year, as well as the whole 6 years leading up to when the claim was made.

It is also important to note that the claim refers to incidents per head, not the actual number. Therefore, a new dataframe column needs to be created which calculates the rate of incidents/offences. The rate per 100,000 of the population will be used in this instance as a per head figure would produce a very low decimal number which is not suitable for analysis.

When the data is ready to be analysed, measures of central tendency will be calculated alongside the standard deviation. Initially, this will give an indication of the shape of the overall distribution and whether there are any outliers. A histogram will then be used to visualise the distribution and help confirm whether any assumptions made about the data are correct. This is important as the type of distribution will dictate what statistical test is used later when claim 3 is analysed.

Returning to claim 2, the top 25 CSP areas with the highest rate of firearms incidents between April 2012 to March 2018 will be selected for analysis. The rate of each one will be presented in a bar chart positioned directly below a second chart displaying the total number of offences for each CSP. The alignment of the bars will allow a direct comparison between the number of offences in an area and the offence rate. This is useful because a CSP might have a higher number of offences than other areas, but a lower offence rate when population is considered.

To complete the analysis of claim 2, a heatmap will show how the offence rate of the top 25 CSPs changes in each financial year of the observed period, as this visualisation is useful at highlighting wider trends [23]. This will also help identify CSPs with the highest offence rate in the years prior to the claim, which may differ from the CSP that has the highest rate over the whole 6-year period.

Exploratory data analysis will be employed again during the initial assessment of claim 3. As this claim concerns a relationship between two variables, a scatter plot will be used to check whether the variables may be correlated and whether the relationship is linear in nature. In addition, the number of firearms and drugs offences for each year will be plotted in a scatter matrix to check whether the relationship varies over time, as inconsistency may indicate the influence of other variables. Moreover, a histogram will be used to visualise the distribution of drugs offences for the whole period, as this will already have been done for firearms offences during the analysis of claim 2.

As alluded to previously, this initial exploration is important as it helps determine which statistical test should be used to quantify the strength of any correlation between two variables. The Pearson correlation coefficient can be used if each variable is normally distributed and there is a linear relationship between them [24]. If either distribution is not normal, Spearman's rank correlation coefficient may be used, as long as the relationship between the variables is monotonic [25].

Once the most appropriate correlation coefficient has been identified, a correlation heatmap will be plotted to visualise the strength of the relationship each year and how this changes over time. The coefficient will also be calculated for all observations between April 2012 and March 2018. The UKs National Crime Agency (NCA) has previously reported a strong connection between drugs supply and the use of firearms [26, p.31], therefore it is expected that there will be a strong positive correlation in this case.

The summary statistics clearly show the presence of one or more outliers in the firearms data. The max value for all variables is significantly higher than the mean and well beyond the range of the standard deviation. The histograms in figure 6 confirm the existence of at least one extreme value and show that the data is not normally distributed, but positively skewed.

The bar charts in figure 7 show that Uttlesford is the CSP area with the highest number and rate of firearm offences by some margin. When compared to the next highest CSP, the number of offences is almost double and the offence rate is around 8 times higher. These figures suggest there may be an error in the data, although this assumption appears to be incorrect. Stansted Airport is situated within the Uttlesford CSP area and was reported to have experienced a dramatic increase in offences during the period of the observations, which included possession of weapons offences [27]. Major airports are situated in or around some of the other CSPs with the highest offence rates, such as Crawley (Gatwick Airport), Windsor and Maidenhead (Heathrow Airport), Manchester, Luton and Liverpool. Despite this, their rates are much lower and it is unclear why Uttlesford and Stansted Airport are an outlier.

Figure 7 also shows that the second highest number of firearms offences between April 2012 and March 2018 were in the Birmingham CSP. If airports are discounted, then the city could be considered to have the highest number of offences in England and Wales during the period. However, the claim refers to the offence rate, not the total number. When population is taken into account, Birmingham's rate puts it in joint 18th place alongside Oldham. Figure 8 also shows that the city wasn't near the top of the offence rate list in any of the years leading up to the claim, even when Uttlesford is excluded.

Turning to claim 3, the scatter plot in figure 9 indicates that firearms and drugs offences are positively correlated and have a linear relationship. This is also apparent in the scatter matrix in figure 11, which shows the relationship between the variables for each financial year. The consistency of the relationship from year-to-year suggests that the correlation is not significantly influenced by another variable.

Neither variable follows a normal distribution, as shown in the histograms in figures 6 and 10. Consequently, the Spearman rank correlation coefficient was used to quantify the strength of the correlation. Figure 12 shows that the coefficient each financial year between April 2012 and March 2018 was 0.77, 0.73, 0.77, 0.75, 0.75 and 0.71 respectively. The tables above also show the coefficient for the whole period; this is 0.83 with the Uttlesford CSP and 0.85 without this outlier. These values demonstrate a high positive correlation between firearms and drugs offences [28].

7. Critical Analysis of Methodology¶

The analysis of claim 1 involved the use of SARIMA and HWES time series forecasting models. One major benefit of SARIMA is that it delivers "near state-of-the-art performance, particularly in cases of small data sets" [18]. In this study, it was relatively easy to implement and produced a model which fits the data quite well. However, selecting the right parameters to solve the optimisation problem is not easy and the grid search method used is considered a brutish approach [29]. Other studies have employed more complex methods such as genetic algorithms and performed well [30]. As such, the SARIMA model could have achieved better results in this case if a different method was adopted, especially since the HWES model performed better without tuning.

Exponential smoothing methods like HWES often achieve good results [31] and are relatively simple to use, as demonstrated above. They work well when the data moves slowly over time [32] and the weight they place on recent data means they are adept at short-term forecasting [33]. Unsurprisingly, this means they are less proficient when forecasting over longer periods, unlike SARIMA which has been shown to be better in these circumstances [17].

Time series methods in general require a large amount of historical data [34], which was not available in this case. This was not an issue as only short-term forecasts were made and the data used was able to achieve credible results. If longer-term forecasts were required then more data would have been needed, ideally several decades worth in order to capture previous cyclical fluctuations. As noted above, the predicted values for both models seemed to continue on an upward trend toward the end of the 24-month forecast when the observed values started to plateau. Therefore, more data may have made the models better at forecasting this change in the observations, particularly SARIMA.

Nevertheless, more data doesn't necessarily mean better predictions as external events may also need to be considered. If so, the SARIMAX method could be a better approach as it uses exogenous variables to represent external factors which might influence the data. For example, public spending on policing and law enforcement is one variable which could affect the rate of violent crime. However, choosing exogenous variables requires domain knowledge and they also need to be forecasted, which can exacerbate the error if long-term predictions are made [35]. Moreover, not all external events can be foreseen, as was the case with the COVID-19 pandemic in 2020.

The use of population data was necessary to calculate the rate of firearms crimes during the analysis of claim 2. This data was taken from the file 'LSOA_pop_v2.csv', which provided the population for each LSOA that was recorded in 2011. Although it subsequently enabled the comparison of crime rates across CSPs for a claim made in 2018, it is important to be cautious when interpreting the results as populations change over time. Similarly, Oliveira [36, p.9] states that "crime often increases with population size at a different pace than per capita", even though linearity is assumed in most cases. He notes this assumption can influence the rankings of cities based on per capita crime rates and advises caution when making comparisons.

The heatmap in figure 8 highlights how the firearms offence rates changed in the highest-ranked CSPs each year. Uttlesford was deliberately excluded from this visualisation as its inclusion would have resulted in the remaining CSPs becoming indistinguishable due to its own strong colouring. This shows that heatmaps can be rendered meaningless if the data behind them contains extreme values.

Correlation was used to assess claim 3 and determine the strength of the relationship between firearms and drugs offences. When using this technique, Aggarwal and Ranganathan [37] warn that outliers and small sample sizes can indicate a relationship between two variables when none exists. The former was negated in this study by calculating the correlation coefficient twice to check whether the outlier Uttlesford significantly influenced the statistic, which it did not. The use of big data means sample size was not an issue, however volume does not necessarily eliminate errors as large datasets can also lead to spurious correlations [38].

It is also important to comment on the data used to analyse the three claims. The UK's ONS previously cast doubt on the reliability of police-recorded crime data in 2014 [39]. This appears to be an ongoing issue as Greater Manchester Police have failed to record a large number of crimes in recent years, with 80,000 being missed between July 2019 and June 2020 [40]. The ONS have also stated that the figures for some crimes like drug possession offences are "heavily influenced by police activities and priorities", meaning they "may not provide an accurate picture of the true extent of criminality" [41]. Additionally, the CSP data used in this study does not always include every crime recorded by a police service, as some occur in areas that do not have a designated CSP and are therefore classified as 'unassigned'. Given these points, the results of any analysis based on UK crime data should be carefully considered.

8. Conclusion¶

The main aim of this project was to assess the validity of the 3 claims made in the documentary Ross Kemp and the Armed Police at the time it was broadcast in September 2018. The first claim stated that violent crime was increasing and time series analysis shows there was an upward trend in these offences from mid-2013 to the time of the broadcast. Therefore, it would be correct to say that violent crime in England and Wales had been increasing at the time of the broadcast, but this cannot be inferred for the whole UK without further statistical analysis.

If time series forecasting had been conducted at the time to predict whether the number of violent crimes would continue to increase, the analysis would have indicated they would. However, the observed values show that these offences started to plateau after the broadcast, meaning the forecasts may have been misleading and led to false claims, particularly if long-term predictions were made. This shows that time series forecasting is not infallible, especially when historical data is limited or unforeseen external events occur.

The second claim stated that there were more firearms incidents per head in Birmingham than anywhere else in the UK. When comparing the Birmingham CSP area against its counterparts across England and Wales, it is clear that the area did not have the highest rate of firearms offences between April 2012 and March 2018 or any of the years leading up to the claim. This is true even when the outlier area of Uttlesford is excluded from the analysis. It may have had the highest number of offences after Uttlesford, but it drops to joint 18th place when population is taken into account.

The data used in the study dictated that the CSP geographical area be used as the basis for comparison when analysing claim 2. It is therefore possible that Birmingham could have had the highest rate if different geography was used, such as the 'built up conglomerations and built up areas' UK census classification that incorporates villages, towns and cities [42]. Nonetheless, even when comparing the city Birmingham to other cities, this study has shown that the City of London, Manchester, Liverpool and Nottingham all had higher rates. As a result, the second claim can be rejected with some confidence as there are other cities in the UK with higher rates of firearms incidents.

Lastly, the third claim stated that crimes involving firearms were closely associated with drugs offences. Again, the period from April 2012 to March 2018 was selected for analysis and correlation was used to assess the relationship between the two variables. The results show that the offences had a high positive correlation over the whole time period and this relationship was consistent from year-to-year. The level of consistency indicates that the relationship isn't overly influenced by other factors like geographical area and the strong correlation between the offences is also evidenced by the National Crime Agency, which has a national remit. Consequently, firearms and drugs offences in England and Wales are closely associated and this is highly likely to be the case across the UK, therefore claim 3 is valid.
